#######################################################
#                                                     #
#               SQLite-php                            #
#                                                     #
#######################################################
#                                                     #
# sqlite-php is a module to interface with the SQLite #
# library, allowing PHP scripts to access/query       #
# SQLite databases.                                   #
#                                                     #
#######################################################


1. Install

To build PHP with SQLite support, you will firstly
need to have SQLite library installed on the target
machine. 

SQLite can be found:
 http://www.hwaci.com/sw/sqlite/

The latest version of SQLite-php can be found on 
 http://sf.net/projects/sqlite-php/

1.1. Static Module

The module directory will need to be placed inside the 
source directory of PHP itself.


# tar zxf php-4.2.1.tgz
# tar zxf sqlite-php-0.0.5.tgz
# mv sqlite-php-0.0.5 php-4.2.1/ext/sqlite


Then you need to run buildconf

# cd php-4.2.1
# ./buildconf

Then configure PHP as you would normaly with the
addition of --with-sqlite on the configure line.

# ./configure --with-sqlite <other options>

Continue the build/install process as normal.

# make 
# make install

1.2 DSO Module

NB: You must already have PHP installed to create a DSO

# tar zxf sqlite-php-0.0.5.tgz
# cd sqlite-php-0.0.5
# phpize
# ./configure --with-sqlite=shared

Copy the sqlite module into your PHP extension directory

# cp modules/sqlite.so /usr/local/lib/php/

(The location of this will depend on what you have set in your
php.ini file, or see http://uk.php.net/manual/en/function.dl.php)

Restart apache.

Load the module either from within your scripts with 
dl("sqlite.so");
or globaly with the following in your php.ini file
extension=sqlite.so



